title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic feat. Anne-Sophie Mutter – “Hedwig’s Theme” From “Harry Potter”
description: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic feat. Anne-Sophie Mutter – “Hedwig’s Theme” From “Harry Potter”\NListen to “John Williams in Vienna”: https://DG.lnk.to/DGWilliams\NSubscribe here for more classical video clips – The Best Of Classical Music: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\N\NHollywood legend John Williams conducted the world-famous Vienna Philharmonic for the very first time in a landmark concert of his best-loved movie music in January 2020. Nominated for 52 Oscars, Williams has composed the soundtracks of our lives with his scores for “Jaws”, “Star Wars”, “Indiana Jones”, “Jurassic Park” and many more. For the concert held at Vienna’s Musikverein Williams is joined by violinist Anne-Sophie Mutter for a series of the virtuosic adaptations written specially for her, including “Hedwig's Theme” From “Harry Potter”, continuing an artistic partnership formed last year for Deutsche Grammophon’s album “Across The  Stars”. The live recording is available now. title: Theme (From "Sabrina" / Audio)
description: In the midst of his work on Star Wars’ Final Episode IX John Williams has created and conducted a complete album with Anne-Sophie Mutter and in mutual admiration. It presents his personal selection of iconic themes as well as rediscovered gems from more than 40 years of his music for film. Recorded at the iconic Sony Pictures scoring stage in Los Angeles where many of the great film scores were recorded, including those of The Wizard of Oz, Gone with the Wind, Lawrence of Arabia, An American in Paris, E.T. and Schindler’s List, among many, many others. “That’s the wonderful thing about John’s music – it exists even without the film.” – Anne-Sophie Mutter\NAnne-Sophie Mutter - Theme From "Sabrina" / Pseudovideo\NListen on a streaming platform of your choice: https://dg.lnk.to/MutterWilliams\N\N#ClassicalMusic #AnneSophieMutter #JohnWilliams\N\N\NMusic video by Anne-Sophie Mutter, The Recording Arts Orchestra of Los Angeles, John Williams performing Theme (From "Sabrina" / Audio). © 2019 Deutsche Grammophon GmbH, Berlin\N\Nhttp://vevo.ly/DpMvdO

title: Anne-Sophie Mutter & John Williams – 'Nice To Be Around' from Cinderella Liberty
description: Anne-Sophie Mutter & John Williams – 'Nice To Be Around' from Cinderella Liberty\NDiscover “John Williams in Vienna”: http://dg.lnk.to/Williams \NWatch the full concert on DG Stage on July 10: https://www.umgt.de/stage_williams_YT\N\NUnder the direction of legendary film composer John Williams himself, violinist Anne-Sophie Mutter and the Boston Pops Orchestra perform a stunning new adaptation of Williams’ “Nice To Be Around” from the jazz-inflected “Cinderella Liberty” score at the Tanglewood Music Festival 2019. Williams’ remarkable ability to recast his famous music in creative new forms is on display in this new version of “Nice To Be Around”, a work chosen for their recent collaboration “Across the Stars”, where Mutter’s bluesy opening is transformed into something hopeful.\N\N\NAnne-Sophie Mutter & John Williams – 'Nice To Be Around' from Cinderella Liberty\NDiscover “Across the Stars”: https://DG.lnk.to/MutterWilliams\NSubscribe here – The Best Of Classical Music: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG \N_______________\N\NFind Deutsche Grammophon Online\N\NHomepage: http://deutschegrammophon.com\NFacebook:  http://fb.com/deutschegrammophon\NTwitter:   http://twitter.com/dgclassics\NInstagram:  http://instagram.com/dgclassics\NNewsletter:  http://deutschegrammophon.com/gpp/index/newsletter\N\N_______________\N\N最高のクラシック音楽―登録はこちら: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\N最优质古典音乐 – 此处订阅: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\NЛучшая Классическая Музыка - Подписаться: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\NLa mejor música clásica - Suscríbase aquí: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\NLe meilleur de la musique classique. title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – Williams: Imperial March (from “Star Wars”)
description: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – Williams: Imperial March (from “Star Wars”)\NDiscover “John Williams in Vienna”: http://dg.lnk.to/Williams \N\NJohn Williams’ movie soundtracks are among the best-loved of all time. Before a single note had been played at the Hollywood legend’s debut concert with the Vienna Philharmonic, Maestro Williams received a standing ovation. Their sensational performance of the “Imperial March” from “Star Wars” underlined the rapport and affection between orchestra and composer. “It was honestly one of the best presentations of that March I’ve ever heard”, Williams reflected afterwards. “They played it as though they owned it.” \N\NDeutsche Grammophon releases Williams’ historic Vienna Philharmonic debut concert in audio and video formats. 'John Williams in Vienna' is now available! title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – “The Rebellion Is Reborn” from “Star Wars: The Last Jedi”
description: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – “The Rebellion Is Reborn” from “Star Wars: The Last Jedi”\NListen to “John Williams in Vienna”: https://DG.lnk.to/Williams\NSubscribe here for more classical video clips – The Best Of Classical Music: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG\N\N“May the Force be with you”: thus the famous greeting and wish from Star Wars. It has a much deeper meaning than the standard “Good luck”, for luck is not enough: skill and craftsmanship are also needed,  as is the ability to employ both of them correctly and successfully. John  Williams already had this kind of “Force” when he published his first piano sonata as an unknown 19-year-old. “The Force” has been with him ever since.\N \NThe legendary American composer John Williams’ stature in the industry was consolidated by Jaws (1975) and Star Wars (1977). His movie soundtracks have earned countless prestigious awards, including five Oscars, five Emmys, four Golden Globes and twenty-five Grammys. As he thanked the audience at Vienna’s Musikverein for their welcome, however, he told them that the invitation to work with the Wiener Philharmoniker was “one of the greatest honours of my life”. \N\NDeutsche Grammophon released Williams’ historic Vienna Philharmonic debut concert in audio and video formats.
